        "comment": {
            "name": "comment",
            "type": "com.atlassian.jira.issue.fields.CommentSystemField",
            "value": [
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/46208",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=adamlundrigan",
                        "name": "adamlundrigan",
                        "displayName": "Adam Lundrigan",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "This is the expected behavior of Zend_Ldap.  If Zend_Ldap::bind() fails to bind, it throws an exception of type Zend_Ldap_Exception.  The examples on the documentation pages don't do it, but you're Zend_Ldap code should look like this:\r\n{code}\r\n$ldap = new Zend_Ldap($options);\r\ntry {\r\n    $ldap->bind();\r\n    [...your LDAP actions here...]\r\n} catch ( Zend_Ldap_Exception $e ) {\r\n    [...handle case where LDAP can't connect...]\r\n}\r\n{code}\r\n\r\nThe unit tests in Zend_Ldap_BindTest do this as well.  For example:\r\n{code}\r\npublic function testEmptyOptionsBind()\r\n{\r\n    $ldap = new Zend_Ldap(array());\r\n    try {\r\n        $ldap->bind();\r\n        $this->fail('Expected exception for empty options');\r\n    } catch (Zend_Ldap_Exception $zle) {\r\n        $this->assertContains('A host parameter is required', $zle->getMessage());\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n{code}",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=adamlundrigan",
                        "name": "adamlundrigan",
                        "displayName": "Adam Lundrigan",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2011-04-29T17:09:35.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2011-04-29T17:12:16.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/46214",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=fominomato",
                        "name": "fominomato",
                        "displayName": "Andre Guariento",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Well, this occurred when the LDAP server was not returned information or took too long to return, I believe that the library was a mistake to delay this because, simply stop the process of research and class error \"LDAP exception\" did not return anything but null.\r\n\r\nMy resolution of the problem was put in the search method from the library the output to 'catch (Exception) \"and so get the exception error in communication.\r\n\r\nAs this error was not provided an instability in our LDAP servers do not believe I need to roast our brains to solving a complex.\r\n\r\nI used google translate to translate this text, sorry.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=fominomato",
                        "name": "fominomato",
                        "displayName": "Andre Guariento",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2011-04-29T17:55:06.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2011-04-29T17:55:06.000+0000"
                }
            ]
        }
